# Title:  

# Objective

To understand the following areas of affected countries to establish core and pressing need for a comprehensive frame for further research and identify mechanism for policy decision:
- knowledge of cannabis
- attitudes of cannabis
- movitation and behaviors of using cannabis now and in the future and people around them
- cannabis vs. cigarate vs. drugs

It will provide baseline information of risk communication to potential users/targets 

# Introduction

- a bit of history of cannabis in general medically, culturally and legally
- current stage of legalizing cannabis
- vs. the history of cigarate and youth

# Summary:
The World Health Organization (WHO) has declared that the Ebola epidemic in Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) 2019 is a public health emergency of international concern.   The 2014–2015 epidemic of Ebola virus disease (EVD) in West Africa affected more than 28,000 persons and caused over 11,000 deaths ( WHO Ebola situation report, 2016) The outbreak of EVD in West Africa was declared a public health emergency of international concern by the World Health Organization (WHO).   Since 2018, more than 1800 were killed related to EVD in Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), and WHO declared the DRC outbreak a global health emergency in July 2019.

RQ:
- evaluate the effectiveness of EVD prevention promotions in the Gambia and to assess the psychosocial factors that steer three behaviors: handwashing with soap, calling the EbolaHotline, and not touching a person who might be suffering from EVD. In 2015, data were gathered from 498 primary care providers. The questionnaire was based on psychosocial factors from the risks, attitudes, norms, abilities, and self-regulation (RANAS) model. (PMID: 31174301 )
- Violence and community mistrust hamper Ebola response. (PMID: 30385158)
- In Congo, fighting a virus and a groundswell of fake news. (PMID: 30655420, ’19,)
- Effectively Communicating the Uncertainties Surrounding Ebola Virus Transmission. (PMID: 26512988, 15)
- Ebola: improving science-based communication and local journalism. (PMID: 26638957, 15)




